      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver must have documented V&V test suite with traceability to ASME V&V 10 and version-controlled build; all hemolysis sub-model routines must have unit-level regression tests.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1 is used with documented release notes and regression suite. However, the user-defined hemolysis damage accumulation subroutine (UDF) lacks a formal unit-test harness; only integration-level testing was performed. Achieved level 3 (solver QA documented, UDF testing incomplete) against required level 4 (full QA including UDF unit tests)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) or equivalent must be applied to the hemolysis transport equation and Navier-Stokes solver to confirm implementation correctness at the expected order of accuracy.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification was completed for the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations confirming second-order spatial accuracy. The power-law hemolysis damage model implementation was verified only via comparison to an analytic Couette-flow solution, not via full MMS. This constitutes partial code verification; achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Formal grid convergence study with GCI ≤5% for primary hemolysis QoI across all 5 operating points; temporal convergence demonstrated for transient impeller passage.",
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation on three mesh densities yields GCI of 3.2–4.8% across all operating points, satisfying the ≤5% criterion. Temporal convergence confirmed with time-step halving showing <1% change in cycle-averaged NIH. Achieved level equals required level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental validation data must be collected at operating conditions spanning the full COU envelope (5 flow-speed combinations); fluid properties must match clinical blood analogue within specified tolerance.",
      "rationale": "Experimental data covers 4 of 5 target operating points; the highest-speed low-flow corner condition (2 L/min, 4500 RPM) was not tested experimentally due to pump cavitation risk in the test loop. Blood analogue viscosity matched within 3% at 37°C. Incomplete operating condition coverage limits achieved level to 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative agreement metric (e.g., E_rel) must be ≤10% for NIH at all tested operating points; uncertainty bounds must be reported and compared.",
      "rationale": "Mean relative error across 4 tested points is 11.4%, marginally exceeding the 10% criterion. Systematic over-prediction at high-speed low-flow condition contributes disproportionately. Uncertainty intervals were reported via Monte Carlo UQ but the 95% prediction interval fails to enclose the experimental outlier at one operating point. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (NIH) must be directly mapped to the clinical acceptance criterion (absolute hemolysis threshold) with documented traceability; sensitivity of NIH to model inputs must be quantified.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the regulatory QoI and is directly compared to the absolute clinical threshold. Sobol sensitivity indices were computed for 6 model inputs; however, the mapping from NIH to patient plasma free hemoglobin concentration—the actual clinical endpoint—relies on a literature-derived empirical factor with uncertainty not formally propagated. This indirect mapping gap reduces achieved level to 3 against required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must use the same pump geometry, operating range, and blood analogue as the COU; any gap between validation scenario and COU must be formally assessed via extrapolation uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Validation used the FDA generic pump geometry, not the proprietary VAD geometry of the COU device. Geometric similarity was assessed qualitatively; quantitative extrapolation uncertainty from the generic to the proprietary geometry was not formally bounded. This geometry gap is the primary driver of the large gap between achieved level 3 and required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated to residual levels below 1e-5 for all transport equations; round-off error analysis must confirm double-precision arithmetic is sufficient for hemolysis accumulation.",
      "rationale": "Continuity residual converges to 1e-4 rather than the required 1e-5 at the high-speed operating point due to rotating reference frame instability. Double-precision arithmetic confirmed adequate. Incomplete iterative convergence at one operating point limits achieved level to 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation workflow with peer review; boundary condition selection, turbulence model choice, and hemolysis model constants must be traceable to COU-specific justification with independent review.",
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow is documented in an internal technical report. Turbulence model selection (SST k-ω) is justified by literature precedent but not by a formal sensitivity study for this specific geometry. Hemolysis model constants (α, β exponents) were taken from Giersiepen et al. without re-calibration or sensitivity assessment. No independent peer review of the setup was conducted. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The hemolysis damage model form (power-law vs. strain-based vs. mechanistic) must be justified for the shear stress and exposure time regime of the COU; model-form uncertainty must be quantified by comparison to at least one alternative formulation.",
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen power-law model is used without comparison to alternative formulations (e.g., Arora mechanistic model or Faghih-Sharp strain-based model). Model-form uncertainty is acknowledged qualitatively but not quantified. At MRL 5, formal model-form uncertainty quantification is required; this represents the largest single credibility gap. Achieved level 2 against required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs (geometry, fluid properties, boundary conditions, hemolysis model constants) must have documented sources, uncertainty ranges, and sensitivity rankings; Monte Carlo UQ must propagate input uncertainties to NIH output.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ was performed for fluid viscosity, inlet flow rate, and rotational speed (3 of 6 identified uncertain inputs). Hemolysis model constants (α, β) and wall roughness were treated as deterministic despite known variability. Partial input uncertainty propagation limits achieved level to 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental hemolysis measurements must be replicated across at least 3 independent test samples per operating point to characterize biological and device-to-device variability; coefficient of variation must be reported.",
      "rationale": "Morrison 2022 dataset includes duplicate (n=2) measurements at each operating point rather than the required triplicate (n≥3). Coefficient of variation ranges from 4.1% to 12.7% across operating points. Insufficient replication prevents robust estimation of biological variability. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Equivalency between validation experiment input parameters and COU operating conditions must be formally demonstrated; any non-equivalency must be bounded by extrapolation uncertainty analysis.",
      "rationale": "This factor was flagged as an epistemic gap at MRL 5. The validation experiment used a porcine blood analogue at 25°C while the COU specifies human blood at 37°C. Temperature and species differences affect both viscosity and red blood cell fragility. No formal equivalency mapping or extrapolation uncertainty was performed. Factor status set to not-assessed; achieved level 2 reflects partial informal comparison only."
    }
